Official Course Description:
Decisions on the design and operation of logistics systems require a thorough understanding of the system's behavior. In many cases logistics systems are too complex to develop analytical methods that can be used to predict the system's behavior and any implementation of changes bears a great risks on the overall performance of the system. Simulation can be used to derive insight about the behavior of complex systems before changes are implemented. In this lab course, students will learn how to develop and conduct simulation experiments to analyze the behavior of discrete-event systems. This lab course will be based on the lecture “Modelling & Simulation in Supply Chain Management” 
The main intended aims of the course: 
- create and implement simulation models; 
- conduct simulation experiments in commonly used software; 
- analyze results; 
- create/ change existing processes. 

At the end of this course students 
- will understand the nature of simulation: systems, models and simulation; 
- understand modelling and discrete event simulation; 
- are able to apply simulations to analyze processes; 
- are able to analyze the outputs: statistics, significance etc.; 
- have learned how to use simulation for optimization; 
- will be able to understand and analyze simulation studies (performed by others) and their outcome; 
- gained knowledge of commonly used software. 

Proposed Content & Format 
This course is the corresponding lab course for the lecture on Modelling & Simulation in Supply Chain Management. In this lab, students apply the knowledge gained in the lecture themselves. They will implement and conduct discrete event simulation experiments and analyze them. 
Participants will have to present simulation studies and have to contribute to lab exercises.

The aim of this introductory course is to familiarize incoming SCEM Master students with standards of academic work expected at Jacobs University Bremen. Participants learn about doing research and academic writing in English, practice writing different components of research texts; learn how to prepare a poster for academic presentations; and finally discuss their work and progress in an individual consultation with the instructor. 
The aim of the course is to gain more knowledge about academic work in English and be able to use it with confidence. 
By the end of this course, students will 
- be able to logically structure a paper and a poster; 
- use appropriate vocabulary, grammar, and style; 
- know the basic facts about preparing an acceptable bibliography; 
- know how to avoid unintentional plagiarism; 
- know about the code of academic integrity. 

Proposed Content & Format 
The course is composed of lectures, in-class individual and group assignments, and homework. 
Grading criteria are: active participation (including poster presentation), four writing tasks (homework), individual consultation, final writing assignment.

This course deals with an in depth introduction to condensed matter and 
solid state physics. Topics include forms of condensed matter, crystal types and crystal structure, density-functional theory, the models by Drude and Sommerfeld, Bose/Fermi distribution, Fermi sphere, cohesive energy, classical and quantum harmonic crystal, phonons and quasiparticles; 
the structure and dynamics of solids, band theory and electronic properties, optical properties, magnetism, superconductivity.

